issue.title: feature request: pass array to `files`
issue.body:
it would be interesting to send more than one patern in the same step, I end up having to duplicate it because I need to send .zip and .tar.gz

### currently

```YAML
      - name: Upload binaries and libaries to github (tarballs)
        uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
        with:
          files: "*.tar.gz"

      - name: Upload binaries and libaries to github (zippies)
        uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
        with:
          files: "*.zip"
```

### suggestion

```YAML
      - name: Upload binaries and libaries to github
        uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
        with:
          files:
            - "*.tar.gz"
            - "*.zip"
```

comment.body:
Github actions only supports strings at this time so I need to work within those design constraints. The multi line syntax in the readme is yaml syntax for a multi line at string

I’m the suggestion above you are double quoting that string but placing quotes inside that string. Try removing those

```yaml
- name: Upload binaries and libaries to github
uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
with:
  files: |
    *.tar.gz
    *.zig
```

issue.title: Sequential upload
issue.body: Currently [assets are uploaded concurrently](https://github.com/softprops/action-gh-release/blob/cd28b0f5ee8571b76cfdaa62a30d51d752317477/src/main.ts#L70). We have around 1400 release files and github does not like so many concurrent uploads - as they also state in their best practices - in my fork I added a parameter that allows to switch to sequential uploads instead. Ist this a feature you'd be interested in? If so, I would prepare a PR.

comment.body:
> 1400 release files

I’d rather not optimize for this case at this point in time. That seems like a lot to ask users to down loaded these individually. An alternative would be to create an archive, zip or tar, file that contains a bundle of them

issue.title: 2 API "calls" per asset upload
issue.body:
I am wondering if you know more about this: Github counts an asset upload as two actual API calls. I placed multiple rate limit logs because it seemed strange to me that uploading 1400 files made me run into rate limits during the second deployment. Turns out the call to the asset upload endpoint is counted as two calls.

Before contacting github about this I was wondering if this is something you noticed too?

comment.body: I have not ran into this issue myself but a possible work around is to create an archive file containing the files used as release assets

issue.body: As title says

comment.body:
I'm using @msailes https://github.com/msailes/lambda-java17-layer project it it seems to work just fine for now

for those using sam you need only to copy that projects zip to a bucket

```
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSfL https://github.com/msailes/lambda-java17-layer/releases/download/v0.0.1-alpha/java17layer.zip -O > java17layer.zip	
echo "1db3dfa9cf07f22447641be476fedbaa125778b8150cbe8573b4b51ea9fe27b4 java17layer.zip" | sha256sum -c
aws s3 cp java17layer.zip s3://{YOUR_BUCKET_NAME}/layers/
```

then refer to the layer from your sam template in a layer version, add that layer your lambda and use the `provided` runtime

```yaml
AWSTemplateFormatVersion: "2010-09-09"
Transform: AWS::Serverless-2016-10-31

Resources:
  Layer:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::LayerVersion
    Properties:
      LayerName: java-17-runtime
      ContentUri: s3://{YOUR_BUCKET_NAME}/layers/java17layer.zip
      CompatibleRuntimes:
        - provided
   Function:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::Function
    Properties:
      CodeUri: path/to/your/app.zip
      Handler: com.you.your.Handler
      Runtime: provided.al2
      Layers:
        - !Ref Layer
      Architectures:
        - arm64
```

issue.body:
it would be interesting to send more than one patern in the same step, I end up having to duplicate it because I need to send .zip and .tar.gz

### currently

```YAML
      - name: Upload binaries and libaries to github (tarballs)
        uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
        with:
          files: "*.tar.gz"

      - name: Upload binaries and libaries to github (zippies)
        uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
        with:
          files: "*.zip"
```

### suggestion

```YAML
      - name: Upload binaries and libaries to github
        uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
        with:

            - "*.tar.gz"
            - "*.zip"

Github actions only supports strings at this time so I need to work within those design constraints. The multi line syntax in the readme is yaml syntax for a multi line at string

I’m the suggestion above you are double quoting that string but placing quotes inside that string. Try removing those

```yaml
- name: Upload binaries and libaries to github
uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
with:
  files: |
    *.tar.gz
    *.zig
```

issue.body:
I am wondering if you know more about this: Github counts an asset upload as two actual API calls. I placed multiple rate limit logs because it seemed strange to me that uploading 1400 files made me run into rate limits during the second deployment. Before contacting github about this I was wondering if this is something you noticed too?

issue.body: As title says

comment.body:
I'm using @msailes https://github.com/msailes/lambda-java17-layer project it it seems to work just fine for now

for those using sam you need only to copy that projects zip to a bucket

```
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSfL https://github.com/msailes/lambda-java17-layer/releases/download/v0.0.1-alpha/java17layer.zip -O > java17layer.zip	
echo "1db3dfa9cf07f22447641be476fedbaa125778b8150cbe8573b4b51ea9fe27b4 java17layer.zip" | sha256sum -c
aws s3 cp java17layer.zip s3://{YOUR_BUCKET_NAME}/layers/
```

then refer to the layer from your sam template in a layer version, add that layer your lambda and use the `provided` runtime

```yaml
AWSTemplateFormatVersion: "2010-09-09"
Transform: AWS::Serverless-2016-10-31

Resources:
  Layer:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::LayerVersion
    Properties:
      LayerName: java-17-runtime
      ContentUri: s3://{YOUR_BUCKET_NAME}/layers/java17layer.zip
      CompatibleRuntimes:
        - provided
   Function:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::Function
    Properties:
      CodeUri: path/to/your/app.zip
      Handler: com.you.your.Handler
      Runtime: provided.al2
      Layers:
        - !Ref Layer
      Architectures:
        - arm64
```

issue.title: Java 17 (Corretto) Runtime
issue.body: As title says

comment.body:
I'm using @msailes https://github.com/msailes/lambda-java17-layer project it it seems to work just fine for now

for those using sam you need only to copy that projects zip to a bucket

```
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSfL https://github.com/msailes/lambda-java17-layer/releases/download/v0.0.1-alpha/java17layer.zip -O > java17layer.zip	
echo "1db3dfa9cf07f22447641be476fedbaa125778b8150cbe8573b4b51ea9fe27b4 java17layer.zip" | sha256sum -c
aws s3 cp java17layer.zip s3://{YOUR_BUCKET_NAME}/layers/
```

then refer to the layer from your sam template in a layer version, add that layer your lambda and use the `provided` runtime

```yaml
AWSTemplateFormatVersion: "2010-09-09"
Transform: AWS::Serverless-2016-10-31

Resources:
  Layer:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::LayerVersion
    Properties:
      LayerName: java-17-runtime
      ContentUri: s3://{YOUR_BUCKET_NAME}/layers/java17layer.zip
      CompatibleRuntimes:
        - provided
   Function:
    Type: AWS::Serverless::Function
    Properties:
      CodeUri: path/to/your/app.zip
      Handler: com.you.your.Handler
      Runtime: provided.al2
      Layers:
        - !Ref Layer
      Architectures:
        - arm64
```
